The Observer



Sir Martin Sorrell: advertising man who made the industry's biggest pitch









Sir Martin Sorrell took over tiny Wire and Plastic Products 25 years ago and turned it into the world's pre-eminent marketing group – ruffling a few feathers along the way















































In 25 years, Sir Martin Sorrell has built WPP into the world's largest advertising and marketing group. Photograph: Micha Theiner/City AM/Rex










WPP



The Observer



Sir Martin Sorrell: advertising man who made the industry's biggest pitch









Sir Martin Sorrell took over tiny Wire and Plastic Products 25 years ago and turned it into the world's pre-eminent marketing group – ruffling a few feathers along the way












Share on Facebook









Share on Twitter









Share via Email
















View more sharing options




Share on LinkedIn









Share on Pinterest









Share on Google+









Share on WhatsApp









Share on Messenger









Close



















David Teather


Saturday 3 July 2010 19.06 EDT


First published on Saturday 3 July 2010 19.06 EDT





When Sir Martin Sorrell got himself a puppy, a red setter, he named it Savage. As our car crawls through central London, from WPP's Mayfair head office to Millbank, where Sorrell is to sit on a panel, the dog sits placidly in the back, lolling its head in the sun. The name couldn't seem less apt. When Sorrell gets out, he offers a firm handshake and urges me to be nice to the mutt. "I called him Savage, because he isn't," he says.
The comment is left hanging in the air, asking to be grasped as a metaphor for Sorrell himself, who comes with a formidable reputation but in the space of the previous hour, squeezed between meetings, is charm itself.
He laughs at being called a "beancounter" and an outsider in the advertising world; he bemoans being stereotyped as a north London Jew; he makes repeated, slightly awkward jokes about his short stature and later sends an email apologising again for turning up late. It is easy to be drawn in. But for all the easy manner and self-deprecation, Sorrell has proven time and again that, unlike Savage, he has considerable bite.
It is 25 years since Sorrell took a loan out against his shares in Saatchi & Saatchi, where he had been finance director, and bought a small company called Wire and Plastic Products, which made wire baskets, and which he would build into the largest advertising and marketing services group in the world.
He has amassed so many companies that he has lost count: "Got no idea, but it is a lot. It is a lot." Some of the larger ones have included the advertising networks J Walter Thompson, Ogilvy & Mather, Grey, and Young & Rubicam; the public relations firms Hill & Knowlton and Burson-Marsteller; and a growing number of digital businesses. Revenues last year reached £8.7bn and the group employs 140,000 people; its big-name clients include Ford, BP, Vodafone and Unilever.
Along the way, he has engaged in some bitterly contested hostile takeovers, including JWT and research business Taylor Nelson Sofres (TNS), making it clear that he is not above putting the odd nose out of joint. David Ogilvy famously called Sorrell an "odious little jerk", although he later had a change of heart, took a job at WPP and became lavish in his praise. Chris Ingram, former boss of media-buying group Tempus, once said he would rather "lick an abattoir floor" than work for Sorrell.
"We've done what are euphemistically called hostile situations," Sorrell says. "It is very interesting. Was it Jimmy Goldsmith [the late financier] who said there is no such thing as a hostile takeover? There isn't really. It is hostile to one person, the chief executive of the target company. It is not hostile to the share owners, it is not hostile to the clients, it is not hostile to the people who work there, so it becomes more personal in that sense."
Sorrell perhaps got some of his ruthless streak from the Saatchis, who, when he worked there, broke the gentlemen's agreement in the industry that agencies did not go after each other's client bases, he says. It was also where he honed his takeover skills. When he assumed control of WPP, the only way to grow quickly was through acquisitions. He set about building a portfolio of "below-the-line" businesses, in less glamorous industries such as direct marketing and sales promotion, "unloved and therefore cheap".
He had no clear idea how big the firm would become, he says, but knew he wanted to do something of size. "I didn't want, forgive the phrase, a Mickey Mouse kind of thing: I wanted to do something of scale. Putting it grandly, from an intellectual point of view, I thought it interesting."
He puts the decision to strike out on his own down to the "andropause" (the male menopause) after reaching 40. The advertising industry at the time, he says, was very "boys' clubby". It was also highly fragmented and consequently didn't reflect the growing global outlook and reach of its clients, making it ripe for consolidation. Plus, "there were very few barriers to entry," he says. "I mean, you needed a desk and a phone. You could go into a hotel and start an agency from a room, which you see in Mad Men."
The deal that announced he had arrived was the $566m takeover of JWT in 1987. "The funniest thing about it was we were in this tiny sort of sub-basement, rather like rats underground, bidding for a company 13 times our size. It was quite amusing." The hostile takeover of O&M for $864m two years later almost bankrupted the business.
He says he rarely sees the Saatchis any more, although he sometimes runs into Charles in Mayfair restaurants. Sorrell has become one of the best known businessmen in Britain but has never been able to shake off his own industry's view that he is something of an interloper: the Harvard-trained financier who ran roughshod over advertising.
Outsider
"I think I am an outsider," he says. "I think when we did our first high-profile deal, which was JWT, I was definitely the outsider. The picture on Ad Age had me in shirt sleeves with a plastic coffee cup and a pen and that was it. 'The Man who Would be King' was the headline. I always remember that, very funny."
A cod psychologist might think his outsider status had driven his desire to emerge as the most powerful figure in the industry, his nose pressed against the windows of advertising's Charlotte Street establishment.
"Well, a psychologist could say I have a Napoleonic complex because of my size. I am exactly the same size as Napoleon, as I have pointed out, and people have criticised me for saying it. Five foot six and a half, which, you know, French metrics, it is five foot four and a half, their feet are 13 inches or something."
It is the third joke he has made about his size in a matter of 15 minutes.
"Well, everybody likes to make it, so I like to sort of do it first," he says. "People say I am an only kid, a spoilt only boy from a middle-class family, I do find it intensely irritating that they always say 'Jewish, north-west London background' – they don't often say 'Catholic, north-east background', or whatever.
"There have been books written about why people do things and don't do things, and they point to things like: I am second generation, my grandparents came from Russia in 1907, you can go through it all … I think I had a pushy mother, a pushy Jewish mother," he laughs, "who used to wrap everything in plastic."
Rich rewards
The business has made Sorrell enormously wealthy – he has banked tens of millions from incentive schemes, £50m in 2005 alone from programmes stretching back a decade, and the stake he still has in the company is worth over £100m. Mention of the criticism directed his way over his rich rewards is the only time he becomes faintly prickly.
Rivals have it differently, he notes. "I think this is a function of the UK. Omnicom can issue options at very low prices with very little criticism. Publicis, quoted in France, can put in incentive schemes without revealing performance criteria."
Senior staff at WPP, he adds, are asked to invest their money in the company and hold the shares for five years before any payouts are possible through its share scheme. "You mention criticism, but what did I do? Virtually with one exception, I kept all my stock for 25 years and suffered with the recent changes in legislation," he says, referring to the increase in capital gains tax.
"The fact that I have held it for 25 years is not taken into any account at all, so I am going to have to pay 10% more, and the person who holds the stock for 25 minutes is treated exactly the same way. It is just not right. That is an incentive to go, not stay."
In a testament to Sorrell's status, George Osborne, the chancellor, recently said the government would change rules on the taxation of foreign earnings, in the hope that WPP would come back to Britain, after decamping to Dublin two years ago.
So will he come back? "I haven't moved, the company has moved. But the pleasing thing is that [the Conservatives] have honoured their election pledge." Revoking taxation of overseas profits "would be very meaningful" he says, "but of course one of the things is that what the coalition government guarantees does not bind the next government." The decision, he says, will be for the board.
Bath-shaped recession
If viewed huffily by his own peers, Sorrell is feted elsewhere, with invitations to the Obama inauguration and to the World Economic Forum in Davos. He has attained fame for his pronouncements on the economy; his comment that the advertising recession at the start of the decade was "bath-shaped" was often repeated. " 'Poor man's sage of Soho', as Michael Grade damningly describes me. It is a putdown, isn't it?" he asks.
His reading of the recent economic runes was LUV-shaped – the "L" representing western Europe, the "U" the United States and the "V'" the fast-growing emergent economies such as China or India. That has since been altered to LVV, reflecting his belief that the US will rebound faster than thought. Providing evidence, WPP's revenues in the first five months of 2010 are up 2% on a like-for-like basis, 5% in May alone. But then in his last big interview with the Guardian in 2008, he said, with some certainty, that there would not be a global recession. He laughs. "We have been pretty accurate after the recession, though."
Tanned and looking at least a decade younger than his 65 years, Sorrell still keeps to a punishing schedule, splitting his time between London and New York. His devotion to the company apparently cost his first marriage, which ended in a £29m divorce settlement in 2005, his former wife complaining she had been "marginalised".
The first half of the interview is in his office, down the road from film director Guy Ritchie's pub, the Punchbowl. The rest is in the car. He pulls out a piece of paper and reads that day's schedule: a presentation to institutional investors, a session with an analyst, lunch with Google, a meeting with a client, this interview, the industry panel and then a business dinner. He doesn't consider retirement. "Only when they shoot me," he says in hushed tones. The increasingly global nature of the business, the fragmentation of media and technology and the ever-quickening pace make it all the more absorbing, he says. But can it just all get too much?
"In a medical sense I probably get stressed, but I don't regard it that way; I am just annoyed when things aren't going right, and it is very personal. You know the [Bill] Shankly quote [about football]: 'It is not a matter of life and death, it is more important.' And that is what WPP is, more important."


