Troubled times at WPP after remuneration vote

As Sir Martin Sorrell’s £13m pay award attracts debate, questions 
  are being asked about the make-up of the board.












Sir Martin Sorrell, chief executive of WPP Photo: Rex Features









 






							By 
											James Quinn

9:02PM BST 16 Jun 2012

Follow


 


 It was the evening of Tuesday February 13, 2007, and in the sumptuous surroundings of the Park Avenue Armory on New York’s Upper East Side, guests listened to Rod Stewart and Patti LaBelle to celebrate a dear friend’s 60th birthday.  Those seated close to the birthday boy – Blackstone chairman Steve Schwarzman – included Sir Martin Sorrell, chief executive of WPP, and Jeffrey Rosen, Lazard banker and the media conglomerate’s senior independent director.  In the speeches that followed the meal of lobster and beef tournedos, Schwarzman even doffed his cap, metaphorically speaking, to Sir Martin, as one of three guests who shared a similar birthday to him, falling a day later on Valentine’s Day. But if there was a lot of love and warm feelings in the room that night among the gathered friends, the atmosphere could not have been more different among the 150 or so people gathered in the somewhat less salubrious confines of Dublin’s The Convention Centre last Wednesday afternoon.  After almost two hours of presentations on the state of the business at the company’s AGM from Sorrell and WPP chairman, Philip Lader, it became clear that the mood was turning against the three men and the rest of the FTSE 100 company’s board. For many, Rosen, there as a board member and chairman of WPP’s remuneration committee, which sets pay, was the problem. The bad feeling was in spite of the fact that slide after slide during the presentation demonstrated WPP’s continued growth, its 18.5pc rise in pre-tax profits to £1bn last year and the fact that it has the fourth best total shareholder return in the FTSE 100. Some £1,000 invested in WPP in 1985 is worth £44,000 today including dividends.  Questions were thin on the ground, but to those present there was only one thing that mattered: the near-£13m remuneration package awarded to Sir Martin for the 2011 financial year, which included a £300,000 rise in his base salary to £1.3m. 
Related Articles



WPP returns to 'Planet No-Growth' Britain

30 Aug 2012



Publicis steps up rivalry with WPP by merging digital agencies

05 Feb 2013



Sorrell on course for a pay cut following revolt

13 Jun 2012



Sir Martin Sorrell's pay in dock but it's WPP board who should take the blame

13 Jun 2012



Fair pay for Sir Martin?

09 Jun 2012



WPP: a history

13 Jun 2012



 As the results of the vote on board pay became known – with 59.5pc of those shareholders who voted coming out against the remuneration report – the board knew it had a major issue on its hands.  For a company whose raison d’être is marketing and communication, it was telling that the leadership had badly misjudged the mood among shareholders and had become the fifth FTSE 100 constituent this year to see a “no” vote on its board pay packages.  While the intricacies of Sir Martin’s pay have been the subject of much debate for the past three weeks, the very make-up of WPP’s board is thought to be one of the other key reasons why it is thought the sizeable “no” vote occurred in the first place.  The 16-man board comprises three executive directors – Sir Martin, and his finance and strategy directors – and 13 non-executives, led by Lader. Of the 13, based on their appointment letters, seven are based in the US, four in the UK, one in China and one in Japan. But the four who appear to be based in the UK, only two – Filtrona chief executive Colin Day and financier Paul Spencer – are actually based here permanently. WPP point to the international nature of the company’s revenues – with only 10pc of revenue in the 2011 financial year coming from the UK – as the reason why the board is so geographically dispersed.  But the fact that WPP’s board members are not majority-based in the country of its primary stock market listing means they appeared to be less aware of the growing political sensitivities around executive pay in the UK that began long before the current “shareholder spring”. On the compensation committee, the American bias is even more stark. Of the five members, only one, Day, is not based in the US.  As one top-15 shareholder said: “It’s all very well having an international board, if they are not alive to the issues the company faces, no wonder things like this [the ‘no’ vote] happen.”  But there are other factors at work within the board dynamic that could also have meant a lack of challenge to the perceived wisdom when it came to setting pay and lack of sensitivity to changing outside events. Tenure is one of them. The longest-serving board director is John Quelch, a British academic now based in Shanghai, who has been on the board for 24 years. A former US investment banker, Bud Morten, has been on the board for 21 years. Mr Lader has been on the board for 11 years. Corporate governance standards suggest a director is no longer deemed to be “independent” after nine years.  Of WPP’s 13 non-executive directors, four fall into this category, while another four are less than a year away from serving three three-year terms.  Although it is not known if Sir Martin and Lader are close beyond the minimum 12 days the chairman’s contract says he must work in return for a fee of £425,000 a year – quite substantial compared with Lloyds Banking Group chairman Sir Win Bischoff who receives £700,000 for working four-days a week – the pair do connect outside business.  Lader is a director of the Atlantic Council, the US-centric think tank, on which Sir Martin sits on the international advisory board. The one-time White House deputy chief of staff is also a senior adviser to Morgan Stanley, one of WPP’s banking advisers. Both Lader and Rosen, who also chairs WPP’s compensation committee and is its senior independent director, are members of the Council on Foreign Relations.  As the birthday bash in New York revealed, Sir Martin and Rosen are both friends of Schwarzman. What is clear is that all three operate in the same circles.  When it comes to pay, although it is Sir Martin facing all the negative headlines, it is the board and the remuneration committee that sets pay, and that process was led by Lader and Rosen.  According to those close to the company, the pair decided not to consult shareholders on Sir Martin’s package following heavy consultation in the prior financial year that led to media leaks and a row about Sir Martin’s remuneration before it had even been decided. One senior source within the company this weekend admitted: “I think that was the basic mistake. It would have been much, much better if they’d continued the consultation process.”  The level of resentment towards the pair was in part reflected in the voting, with 11.8pc voting against Mr Lader’s re-election, and 21.8pc voting against Rosen. In contrast, Sir Martin was voted against by less than 2pc of shareholders.  As Lader and Rosen begin to consult with investors on the next steps – likely to include a possible redrawing of Sir Martin’s pay package along with a potential re-pitch for WPP’s executive pay consultants, Towers Watson – it is clear that the problems that led to the “no” vote in the first place are not necessarily easily resolved.  Insiders with awareness of the proxy votes indicate that institutional voters fell largely into two camps. One, those who chose to back the remuneration report, believed to include BlackRock, Capital and T Rowe Price. The other, who voted against, included Standard Life, Scottish Widows and Hermes.  Among those who chose to vote against, the reasons were mixed. Standard Life is believed to have signalled it did not have a problem with Sir Martin’s pay rise, but it did object to his pension increase. A second blue-chip investor said Sir Martin should only be paid if the share price increases, while another pushed for return on equity to be included in the hurdles required for him to jump to receive his long-term performance awards.  On top of those opinions comes the divergence between the fund managers who buy and manage stakes in the company, and their corporate governance departments, which lead voting at annual meetings.  At a number of major fund managers there is said to have been a distinct difference of opinion on how to vote on pay at the WPP meeting, with the corporate governance department winning on most occasions.  One senior source indicated that the continued political pressure on executive pay – which will this week see Vince Cable unveil a new series of rules on the subject – has in no small part triggered the “Shareholder Spring”.  “Why has all this happened? The reason in part is because the Government, both under Brown and under the Coalition, has said to institutions to act on executive compensation. It is a political issue,” said the source. “If they’re not careful, they’re worried the Government will put their own pay under the microscope, which they don’t want.”  What happens next will be the subject of much debate in coming weeks as Lader and Rosen undertake the difficult task of appeasing shareholders while at the same time not aggravating Sir Martin, who owns a 1.4pc stake in the business worth £134m.  At close of the markets on Friday, WPP was worth £9.5bn. 













